. 1 (2009). 54 Ibid. Protecting the rights of key HIV-affected women and girls in health care settings: A legal scan 23 i Sex work and HIV in South Asia \u2022 Sex workers comprise of 0.5 percent of India\u2019s adult female population and they account for 7 percent of HIV-positive females.55 \u2022 There are an estimated 100,000 sex workers in Bangladesh. HIV prevalence among sex workers in Bangladesh is estimated at less than 1 percent. 56 \u2022 HIV prevalence among Pakistan\u2019s female sex workers is estimated at 0.6 percent.57 \u2022 In Nepal, female sex workers, injecting drug users, and transgender women are particularly vulnerable to HIV, with female sex workers (aged 15 years and above) accounting for approximately 1 percent of all HIV infections.58 Some respondents explained that health service providers in private clinics as well as doctors in the government", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "30bbf3fa-dcac-491a-9748-685c1562acef": {"__data__": {"id_": "30bbf3fa-dcac-491a-9748-685c1562acef", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-rights-key-hiv-affected-women-and-girls-health-care-settings-legal-scan", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Protecting the rights of key HIV-affected women and girls in health care settings: A legal scan", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-rights-key-hiv-affected-women-and-girls-health-care-settings-legal-scan", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "253823e897036fb0d9c06afacb1bcc6eb0814f1d987315dd5360baceb1011db2"}, "3": {"node_id": "70854007-bb9e-406f-ae99-61825c6df922", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-rights-key-hiv-affected-women-and-girls-health-care-settings-legal-scan", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4f760b55819b51e82e57397d300a638fa900482dce5888694e26eac6e012112d"}}, "hash": "010f816fc4230ec0814db9c52b91bc57ee286210d801cfc8a6ba4abdac237557", "text": "hospitals tend to ask personal questions, often loudly and not in a private space, particularly about their work and sexual history. One respondent described being sexually harassed by a male doctor when he realized she was a sex worker. One fifth of the 425 respondent sex workers had never visited a health facility, and many female sex workers limited themselves to using private clinics, non-governmental clinics, and pharmacies to avoid the discrimination and poor treatment meted out to them on the basis of their work.59 According to another study, sex workers in India are \u201ctreated callously in hospitals and clinics, made to wait longer periods to be seen\u2026and are refused treatment until they agree to undergo HIV testing.\u201d60 Being forced into having HIV tests and knowing that the results will not be kept private are another serious deterrent to seeking services. This atmosphere of discrimination and moral censure has, understandably, made many sex workers reluctant to approach health care services. Legal activists have pointed out that state health controls, \u201cthrough measures purportedly serving a public health purpose, are a frequent source of violations of sex workers\u2019 rights: mandatory testing for STIs and HIV; routine infringements of confidentiality regarding HIV test results, and other medical information.\u201d61 Sex work is criminalized in all of the four countries in which this study was conducted, although in Nepal it is the client and not the sex worker who is liable for prosecution. Criminalization affects the efficacy of outreach services and HIV-prevention programmes, making sex workers harder to reach and deterring them from approaching health services in fear of legal consequences. A detailed discussion of this topic is beyond the scope of this paper, but multiple studies have linked criminalization to the lowering of access to services.62 Another important aspect of this has been highlighted in research carried out as part of the work of the 55 National Aids Control Organisation, Department of AIDS Control (Ministry of Health & Family Welfare), Annual Report 2009-2010. 56 UNICEF, \u201cHIV/AIDS in Bangladesh\u201d (updated March 2009); see www.unicef.org/bangladesh/HIV_AIS%281%29.pdf. 57 National Aids Control Programme, Pakistan, Country Progress Report (2012). 58 National Centre for HIV and STD Control, Nepal. 59 Ibid. 60 WHO, Violence Against Women and HIV/AIDS: Critical Intersections, \u201cViolence Against Sex Workers and HIV Prevention,\u201d Information Bulletin Series, no.. 3 (2005), p 2. 61 K. Bhardwaj and V. Divan, Sexual Health and Human Rights - A Legal and Jurisprudential Review of Select Countries in the SEARO Region: Bangladesh, India, Indonesia, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and Thailand (International Council on Human Rights Policy, 2011). 62 John Godwin, Sex Work and the Law in Asia and the Pacific \u2013 Laws, HIV and human rights in the context of sex work (UNAIDS, UNFPA, and UNDP, 2012); Asia-Pacific Regional Dialogue of the Global Commission on HIV and the Law, Issues Brief: Laws and Practices Relating to Criminalization of People Living with HIV and Populations Vulnerable to HIV, (2011); Human Rights Watch, Epidemic of Abuse: Police Harassment of HIV/AIDS Outreach Workers in India, (July 2002); Laws and policies affecting young people\u2019s access to sexual and reproductive health and HIV services in Asia and the Pacific (UNESCO, UNFPA, UNICEF, UNAIDS, and UNDP, 2013). 24 i Global Commission on HIV and the Law, showing that the conflation of the discourse on trafficking with that of sex work has led to increased criminalization of sex work.63 Indeed, all four of the studied countries have enacted anti-trafficking laws64 that include provisions criminalising various aspects of sex work.65 Additionally, being predicated on the assumption that all sex workers are sexually exploited, these laws promote attempts to suppress all sex work \u2013 including \u2018raid and rescue\u2019 interventions, which can result in sex workers being forcibly removed from their workplaces, detained, and mandatorily tested for HIV.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "70854007-bb9e-406f-ae99-61825c6df922": {"__data__": {"id_": "70854007-bb9e-406f-ae99-61825c6df922", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-rights-key-hiv-affected-women-and-girls-health-care-settings-legal-scan", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Protecting the rights of key HIV-affected women and girls in health care settings: A legal scan", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-rights-key-hiv-affected-women-and-girls-health-care-settings-legal-scan", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "253823e897036fb0d9c06afacb1bcc6eb0814f1d987315dd5360baceb1011db2"}, "2": {"node_id": "30bbf3fa-dcac-491a-9748-685c1562acef", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pa