dcient skills regarding male sexual health (pharyngeal and ano-rectal care in particular); insensitive communication and counselling with MSM and transgender clinic clients as signi\ufffdcant impediments for the uptake of services provided in health care settings.\u00b9\ufffd Currently, under the ISEAN-HIVOS Global Fund grant, there is a health sector component focusing on skills training of health care providers providing HIV/STI related services to MSM and transgender people, and reduction of stigma in health care settings in four countries including Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines and Timor-Leste. UNDP as the TA provider for ISEAN-HIVOS project would work with \u00b9\ufffd UN Human Rights Council, Nineteen Sessions, Agenda Items 2 and 8. Annual Report of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights and Report of the O\ufffdce of the High Commissioner and Secretary-General. Discriminatory Law and practices and acts of violence against individuals based on their sexual orientation and gender identity (A/HRC/19/41) 17 November 2011. \u00b9\ufffd Report of the Asia Paci\ufffdc Regional Dialogue of the Global Commission on the HIV and the Law. Bangkok, 17 February 2011. UNDP. \u00b9\ufffd Godwin, J. (2010). Legal Environments, Human Rights, and HIV Responses among MSM and Transgender people in Asia and the Paci\ufffdc: An Agenda for Action. UNDP. \u00b9\ufffd WHO (2011). Prevention and Treatment of HIV and other Sexually Transmitted Infections among Men who have sex with men and Transgender people ANNEX A CONCEPT NOTE 20 Regional Consultation on Improving Access to Prevention, Care and Treatment of HIV among Men who Have Sex with Men and Transgender People WHO (SEARO and WPRO) to support the implementation of this component, starting with development of a training package with reference to the existing regional and newly launched global guidance \"Men who have sex with men and transgender people Prevention and treatment of HIV and other sexually transmitted infections: Recommendations for a public health approach\", which was jointly developed by WHO, UNDP, UNAIDS, MSMGF, and GIZ in 2011. STRATEGY To review the draft training package, WHO will convene a 3-day regional informal experts consultation attended by participants with experience on providing HIV and sexual health services for men who have sex with men and transgender persons. The general objective of the informal consultation is to strengthen the HIV/STI prevention, care and treatment response for MSM and transgender people. The speci\ufffdc objectives are: \uf09f To review the global guidelines and adapt the same for addressing HIV/STIs in the context of the Asia-Paci\ufffdc region. \uf09f Review and discuss the draft regional training package. \uf09f Share country experiences and provide inputs for \ufffdnalization of the training package. \uf09f Develop recommendations for implementation at country level. OUTCOME Improved capacity of health sector practitioners to provide appropriate care to men who have sex with men and transgender persons. PARTICIPANTS WHO will nominate informal experts from the SEARO region who have provided HIV/STI prevention, care and treatment for men who have sex with men and transgender persons.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "01264efd-fef3-4dc9-a022-1226620ce809": {"__data__": {"id_": "01264efd-fef3-4dc9-a022-1226620ce809", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regional-consultation-improving-access-prevention-care-and-treatment-hiv-among-men-who-have-sex-men-and-transgender-people", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Regional Consultat